### Central Thesis
The warmth and the defiance people split Sarandon into are the same Type 8 instrument: she watched her mother feel her life was "done to her" and built everything around never being controlled, paying the cost every time.

### Changes Made (1 total)

**Transition Fixes (1):**
- **Camera-off → Ceasefire:** The section opened on the abstract word "test," a frame the warm preceding section wasn't carrying, leaving the reader to ask "test of what?" Added two short bridge sentences ("That protective drive does not stay inside warm rooms. It is also what gets her fired.") that carry the *protect/protective* keyword from the diagnosis straight into the firing, so the warmth and the cost read as one circuit.

### What Was Preserved
- All frontmatter, working-notes, ledgers, fresh-eyes and second-pass notes
- All Svelte/HTML components (accordion, inner-thought, pull-quote, contrast-panel, Rabbit Hole)
- All internal links and quotes
- 6 of 7 section transitions untouched (already strong)

### Remaining Concerns (your call, not auto-applied)
1. **Diagnosis → Childhood** is adequate, not strong. The diagnosis ends on the Type 1 rebuttal, then drops straight into "She was born Susan Abigail Tomalin in 1946…" The H2 heading does most of the bridging, and the section quickly reaches "the engine is not really the birth order, it is what she saw in her mother," so it self-corrects. I left it alone because any bridge sentence risks reading as a mechanical "now let's look at her childhood." Flagging only so you can judge.
2. **Repetition the second-pass notes already half-addressed:** the mother's "done to her" line still lands ~5 times (epigraph, TL;DR, childhood, twice in the close). It's the spine, so this is a *deliberate* through-line device, not a cohesion break. No change made. If you ever want the final invocation to hit harder, the candidate to drop is the first of the two closing touches, not any earlier one.

